Jack Arent/NBAE/Getty ImagesAlthough the pro game is better suited for Wiggins' skill set, there are still adjustments he can make. As NBA summer league play winds to a close, the urge to make sweeping assumptions about players' NBA potential based on their performances in Las Vegas and Orlando becomes overpowering. The fact of the matter is that summer league should be looked at as a lab: an experimental environment to try new moves and new roles and develop new instincts. Nothing seen here is for certain, but often improvements to a player's game get their first chance to shine in this semicompetitive situation. To read more about how players can improve their game after this year's Summer League, you must be an ESPN Insider. Insider Become an insider and get access to all our articles and tools. Subscribe Sign in View Insider Benefits Â» Magazine subscribers: activate your Insider account. Recommend0 Tweet0 Email Subscribe Amin Elhassan Follow Archive Video coordinator, college scout, Phoenix Suns Assistant director of basketball operations, Phoenix Suns MBA from Arizona State University